@title Leadership Patterns Underpinning the Transformation Cycle
@sigils [🚴/旦 🌄/化]
@illustrates ["Different units (researchers, librarians, IT, governance, funders)" "have complementary strengths rather than identical roles."]
@illustrates ["IT’s constraints differ from REF’s; governance differs from researchers’."]
@illustrates ["Librarians need professional autonomy; IT needs architecture authority;" "researchers need academic freedom."]

! conclusion: Leadership Patterns Underpinning the Transformation Cycle

  + IF: Different units (researchers, librarians, IT, governance, funders) have
        complementary strengths rather than identical roles, with differing
        constraints and needs for professional autonomy, architecture authority,
        and academic freedom.

  + HOWEVER: The transformation cycle is not just procedural (tensions → requirements
             → transparency → feedback → iteration); treating it as procedure alone
             ignores that it is relational and must adjust to each collaborator.

  + THEN: Operate an explicit move on the named axis (see substructure below); steward the pattern against the declared discipline.

Leadership must match connection mode to context and collaborator.

The transformation cycle is not just procedural (tensions → requirements → transparency → feedback → iteration).
                 It is relational, adjusting compatibility, rhythm, worldshape, boundaries,
                 and connection modes to guide the institution through change.

    + clarifies: Emotional economies and meaning structures matter for change readiness.

    + lemma: Closed-loop teams improve through real-time collaboration (e.g., librarians + RDM).

    + lemma: Parallel-loop teams improve through asynchronous work (e.g., researchers + IT).

    + lemma: Some connect through tasks (workflow clarity).

    + lemma: Some through care (trust, safety).

    + lemma: Some through practice (craft, mastery).

    + lemma: Some through mission (values, impact).

  + because: Compatibility Mapping enables collaboration without forcing sameness.

  + because: Different teams require different learning rhythms.

  + because: Each team inhabits a distinct worldshape.

  + because: Boundaries make collaboration healthier, not weaker.

  + because: People connect to work through different modes of intimacy.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Apply Compatibility Mapping to enable collaboration without forcing sameness.
    - Match learning rhythms to each team (closed-loop real-time vs parallel-loop asynchronous).
    - Respect each team's distinct worldshape.
    - Maintain boundaries that make collaboration healthier.
    - Match connection mode (tasks, care, practice, mission) to each collaborator.
